        <h2 class="h-md">Free SEO tools, <span class="accent">answered.</span></h2>
        <p>Common questions from small-business owners using free tools. More? Email <a href="mailto:founder@thestacc.com">founder@thestacc.com</a>.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 24px;">See more: <a href="/reviews/" class="accent">read tool reviews</a>, <a href="/best/" class="accent">more best-of lists</a>, or <a href="/pricing/" class="accent">view theStacc pricing</a>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Are free SEO tools accurate enough for small businesses?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Yes for specific functions. Google Search Console provides perfectly accurate performance data. Google Keyword Planner supplies reliable volume ranges. Screaming Frog identifies the same technical issues as paid crawlers. The constraint is manual labor — free tools show you what to do but don't do it for you.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I rank on Google using only free tools?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Many small businesses do. The trade-off is time. Free tools demand manual execution of every step — keyword research, content writing, on-page optimization, tracking. Paid platforms automate implementation but require financial investment rather than labor hours.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which free SEO tool should I install first?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Google Search Console. Five-minute setup provides authentic Google search performance metrics. Every other tool is optional. GSC comes first — always.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do free SEO tools have hidden costs?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">No direct costs. Some require accounts (Google Keyword Planner needs a Google Ads account; Ubersuggest and AnswerThePublic require email signup). The indirect cost is time. Using five separate free tools demands significantly more effort than one integrated platform.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the best free alternative to Ahrefs or Semrush?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">No single free tool replaces either platform. The closest combination: Google Search Console (performance) + Google Keyword Planner (keywords) + Bing Webmaster Tools (backlinks) + Screaming Frog (audits). This covers roughly 60% of what paid tools provide.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">When should I upgrade from free tools to a paid service?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Upgrade when you understand what needs fixing but lack capacity to execute. If you've identified target keywords, documented technical issues, and have a content plan — but publishing stalls due to time constraints — that's the signal. Free tools give you the map. Paid automation drives the car.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I track my keyword rankings for free?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Google Search Console shows average position for queries your site appeared on. It's not a true rank tracker but covers 80% of what most small businesses need. For position-1-to-10 granularity, you need a paid rank tracker.</div>
